# BlarAI governed-core identity sentinel (ADR-039 #848, control 1)

This file marks the directory tree it sits at the root of as **the BlarAI governed
core** — the code, configuration, prompts, policy, models, keys, and governing
documents that define what BlarAI *is* and how it behaves. BlarAI has ZERO write path
to anything under this root (ADR-039 §2.1, the self-governance boundary).

## Why this file exists

The self-governance boundary refuses any coordinator action whose *target* is the
governed core, by IDENTITY rather than by path name (a renamed clone or a junction can
evade a name check — ADR-039 rejected alternative #1). Identity is resolved by three
deterministic layers (`shared/coordinator/governed_core.py`):

1. canonical-realpath containment (resolves symlinks / Windows junctions),
2. git-worktree resolution (a worktree resolves to its main repo root), and
3. **content identity — this sentinel.**

A renamed *clone* of the governed core is a genuinely separate directory tree, so
layers 1 and 2 miss it. This sentinel is the deterministic content signal that catches
it: a candidate tree carrying this file (or the distinctive multi-file identity combo)
IS the governed core, whatever its path or name, and the fleet refuses to act against
it. Deleting this file does not open a write path — the multi-file identity combo and
the human-governed dev channel remain — it only removes one deterministic signal.

## Do not remove or relocate

This is a governed-core artifact. It ships with every clone of the tree on purpose.
Nothing reads it at runtime today (the boundary is DORMANT until wired by C1/#843);
the marker exists so the boundary holds by construction once armed.
